📖 Theoretical Background
🔒 Cybersecurity in Autonomous Vehicles
Autonomous vehicles rely on interconnected sensors (speed, throttle, brake, GPS, RPM). These systems are vulnerable to cyberattacks such as:
DoS (Denial of Service) → disrupts communication channels.
GPS Spoofing → manipulates navigation data.
Replay/Fabrication Attacks → inject false sensor values.
Fuzzy Attacks → random, unpredictable input signals.
Intrusion detection systems (IDS) use machine learning + fuzzy logic to classify normal vs. abnormal behavior.

🌀 Role of 3D Plots
Axes: Speed (X), Throttle (Y), Brake (Z).
Color coding: Represents detection regions (normal vs. attack).
Purpose: Visualize how combinations of driving parameters cluster into safe vs. suspicious zones.
This helps stakeholders see anomalies at a glance — for example, unusual throttle + brake combinations at high speed may indicate malicious input.

📊 Waveform Analysis
Your multi‑panel plots show how different attacks distort sensor signals over time:
Normal signals remain stable.
Attacks introduce spikes, drops, or irregular oscillations.
Comparing multiple parameters (speed, brake, throttle, RPM) reveals attack fingerprints.

🎯 Insights & Results
Cluster separation in 3D space → ML model successfully distinguishes normal vs. attack states.
Waveform deviations → Each attack type leaves a unique signature, useful for training IDS.
Protocol comparison (FQAR vs RCBA) → Shows trade‑offs in packet delivery and delay, linking network resilience to vehicle safety.

